DIAGNOSIS. Males have the mesonotum distinctly elevated posteriorly (
Fig. 15 I
); the cephalic armature is not fused, the anterior coronals are laterally compressed and rounded apically (
Fig. 15 I
).

Females have a low crest on the head (
Fig. 16 I
); the body armature is never acute and the abdomen is distinctly dilated laterally (
Fig. 16 A
).

